<div class="docs-content__header">
  <span class="docs-content__eyebrow">Get Started</span>
  <h1 class="docs-content__title">Quick Start</h1>
  <p class="docs-content__description">Create your first project, configure an agent-driven column, and run a task &mdash; all in under five minutes.</p>
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <h2 id="create-a-project">Create a Project</h2>
  <p>After signing in for the first time, Master of Puppets launches an <strong>onboarding wizard</strong> that walks you through creating a project, choosing an adapter, and seeding the default board &mdash; the fastest path from a fresh install to a working pipeline.</p>
  <p>You can also skip the wizard and click <strong>New Project</strong> from the dashboard at any time. Give your project a name &mdash; this is the isolated workspace where all your columns, tasks, and runs will live. Master of Puppets automatically seeds the project with the system columns (<code>backlog</code>, <code>in_progress</code>, <code>review</code>, <code>done</code>, <code>cancelled</code>, <code>blocked</code>) and a starter skill library.</p>

  <h2 id="meet-the-board">Meet the Board</h2>
  <p>Open the <strong>board</strong>. Each column on it has a <em>transition policy</em>:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Manual</strong> columns are queues &mdash; humans drag tasks in and out.</li>
    <li><strong>Agent</strong> columns run an AI adapter automatically whenever a task lands in them.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Tasks flow left-to-right through the columns you arrange. There are no roles or hierarchies; the column is the unit of orchestration.</p>

  <h2 id="add-an-agent-column">Add an Agent Column</h2>
  <p>Click <strong>New Column</strong>. Give it a clear name like "Implement" or "Triage" &mdash; this is the name people and agents will use in <code>@</code>-mentions. Set the <strong>transition policy</strong> to <em>agent</em> to reveal the adapter and prompt fields.</p>
  <p>Fill in a <strong>job spec</strong> describing what should happen to a task while it sits in this column, and <strong>success criteria</strong> the agent should check before declaring the task done. Both go into the system prompt the agent receives on every run.</p>
  <p>Optionally attach <strong>skills</strong> from the project library to give the agent specific capabilities, and set a per-month <strong>budget</strong> in cents to cap spend.</p>

  <h2 id="configure-an-adapter">Configure an Adapter</h2>
  <p>Pick an adapter for the column:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Claude Code</strong> &mdash; run Claude CLI locally with streaming output and resumable sessions. Set the model (e.g., <code>claude-sonnet-4-6</code>) and you're ready.</li>
    <li><strong>HTTP API</strong> &mdash; point to any cloud-hosted agent endpoint.</li>
    <li><strong>OpenCode</strong> &mdash; use OpenCode CLI with any supported provider (OpenAI, Gemini, Groq, etc.).</li>
    <li><strong>Codex</strong> &mdash; run OpenAI Codex CLI locally, targeting OpenAI or Ollama, with per-column sandbox and approval policies.</li>
    <li><strong>Shell Command</strong> &mdash; run a custom script or CLI tool.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>For this quick start, Claude Code is the fastest path. Set the model and optionally configure a working directory where the agent will operate.</p>

  <h2 id="drop-in-a-task">Drop in a Task</h2>
  <p>Create a task and place it in your new agent column &mdash; either by creating it there directly, or by moving it across the board. The moment the task enters an agent-driven column, the adapter starts running. There is no separate "dispatch" step.</p>
  <p>Set a priority if needed. Tasks within a column are sorted by position by default.</p>

  <h2 id="watch-it-run">Watch It Run</h2>
  <p>Open the column to see its <strong>runs</strong> &mdash; streaming output appears in real time as the agent works. When the agent finishes, it advances the task to the next column, rejects it back, or blocks it &mdash; with a stated reason recorded in the audit log.</p>
  <p>From here you can chain more agent columns together, insert manual <em>review</em> columns where humans approve or reject results, and set budgets to govern spend. See the guides for deeper walkthroughs.</p>
</div>
